The game is fun, but the controls will get you killed often. It's not like they're bad, either. They're made well for a game that wasn't originally designed for smartphones. The thing is, enemies will attack you from anywhere, so when you have a thumb taking up space on your screen, you'll be left vulnerable to incoming enemy projectiles from certain angles. The game and its sequel are dirt cheap, so if you can adjust to the controls, then you're in for a treat.

I was reasonably satisfied with this conversion of R-Type at first. Everything you remember from the arcade game seems intact, but swiping a finger across the screen to control your ship is a bit of a kludge. However... if you connect a USB controller to an On-The-Go adapter, and the adapter to your Android device, the game transforms into a thing of beauty. There's no need to configure the joystick or turn on any hidden options... it just works. I'm amazed! If only other Android games were this controller friendly! Thumbs way up, into the heavens.

The R-Type series has always been among my absolute favorite SHMUPs period (and I'm not a fan of bullet pattern SHMUPs so it's good to come back to it.)  I was a bit excited at the prospect of having a native Android port rather than some emulation.  However, I think an emulator would be preferable.  First, it runs horribly on my Samsung Galaxy S3 even with the CPU set to full speed and performance mode.  (Low framerates, sluggish unresponsive controls, and etc.)  It runs fine on my Nexus 7, so I have to assume it's just not properly compatible somehow (even though that shouldn't be possible.)  Second, the game really needs to be played with the "arcade" controls, but they made them too small!  Even on the Nexus 7 it's very hard to control the virtual d-pad because it's so small.  And this is coming from someone with small hands.  They should have had some basic adjustment even if only the option to change between three preset sizes or something.  Similarly, you can't really use the fire button while pressing the force button without some serious hand Twister.  It should have been placed horizontally I guess.  You can't charge and control the force at the same time.
